Symbolic Rendering v1.0

A Pantheon pattern for drawing with language

Definition
Symbolic Rendering is the practice of producing visual artifacts using text tokens as marks on a discrete grid, where meaning comes from spatial arrangement + density + repetition, not from photoreal pixels.

1) Core idea
	•	A “canvas” is a 2D grid of characters.
	•	Characters are “ink marks.”
	•	Visual tone (light/dark), texture, depth, and edges come from mark density and local contrast.

2) Rendering primitives

Canvas
	•	Width W, height H, monospaced.

Mark set (pointillism palette)
	•	Light: .
	•	Mid: · :
	•	Dark: * o
	•	Deep shadow: #

Rules
	•	Tone = density: more marks per area → darker.
	•	Edges = gradients: change density gradually across a boundary.
	•	Depth = atmospheric perspective: distant objects use lighter marks + less contrast.
	•	Texture = noise: small random variation in marks within a tonal band.
	•	Highlight = subtraction: leave space or use only . in bright regions.

3) Pipeline (Letter-to-Garcia version)
	1.	Compose: Decide horizon line, main silhouette, foreground anchors.
	2.	Block values: Lay in large tonal regions with ./·/:.
	3.	Define edges: Add */o where transitions sharpen.
	4.	Shadow pass: Add # only where the deepest occlusion is required.
	5.	Atmosphere pass: Reduce contrast with distance (replace o/# → :/·).
	6.	Kintsugi repair: If a region “breaks” (reads wrong), fix by smoothing gradients, not by adding detail.

4) What it’s good for
	•	Diagrams, maps, “mood boards,” concept sketches
	•	Governance-safe visuals (fully auditable, reversible)
	•	Rapid iteration (edit marks like code)

5) Boundaries (so it stays honest)
	•	It is not photorealism.
	•	It depends on a monospace display and human perceptual completion.
	•	It’s a rendering grammar, not a vision model.

⸻

Example: Pointillism-style landscape of Chantal’s Cathedral

(Monospace recommended. This is deliberately “dotty” and impressionistic.)

